## B.5 Displacement Spectrum Table

Not all AI-driven displacement is equal. The following table provides a structured taxonomy for risk-stratified disclosure requirements:

| Displacement Level | Description | Examples | Minimum Disclosure Requirement |
|-------------------|-------------|---------|-------------------------------|
| **Low** | AI augments human task; human retains full decision authority; no labor substitution | Spell check, scheduling suggestions, data formatting | Disclose AI involvement; provide opt-out |
| **Moderate** | AI provides recommendations that humans routinely accept; some deskilling risk | Route optimization, claim triage, diagnostic flagging | Disclose model logic for recommendations; disclose override rate; monitor skill retention |
| **High** | AI makes primary decision; human review is nominal or post-hoc | Automated loan approval, resume screening, content moderation at scale | Full pattern disclosure; appeal mechanism; regular bias audits; human review on demand |
| **Structural** | AI replaces entire role categories; displacement is institutional, not individual | Automated customer service, fully automated permitting | R_w assessment required; workforce impact disclosure; R_w = 0 certification or public statement of exception |
| **Catastrophic** | AI-driven displacement at scale without transition support; AIRD-producing conditions | 4,000+ role eliminations attributed to AI without retraining (Block Inc. 2026) | Public disclosure of displacement impact; AIRD screening for affected workers; regulatory notification |

